:::summary
Sir Isaac Newton (1643–1727) was an English mathematician, physicist, astronomer, and theologian — one of the most influential scientists in human history. He formulated the laws of motion and universal gravitation, co-invented calculus, and his work laid the foundation for classical mechanics and the scientific worldview for over two centuries. Newton was deeply religious and believed his scientific work revealed the handiwork of God.
:::

